pr_title: Transport to NoteController and ES6 refactor and code cleanup of turtle.js
pr_body:
This pull request contains two things:

- I've extracted out `_playNote`, `_playSwing`, `_playDotted` from `js/blocks/RhythmBlocks.js`, and `_processNote` from `logo.js`, to a new file `note.js`, and appropriate additions and reference changes. This one should be fine since I mostly just had to cut and paste, except a few changes, which are mostly tested. This is an experimental feature - I'll eventually modify it after further discussion, but these needed to be extracted, so I think they can be merged as of now.

- I've refactored `turtle.js` to ES6 standard completely: `var` to `let`, `arrow` functions, and `class` declarations. In addition I've done some cleanup w.r.t. whitespaces and comments. Since, a lot of functions have been touched, some of them heavily, I think they need to be tested thoroughly. I have, however, done some basic tests, and they are fine.

pr_title: Port out notation related members to another file (with Notation class)
pr_body:
.. touches quite a few files :p

Created a new class called `Notation` in a new file `notation.js`. Instantiated it from within `Logo`, then used that `object` to address all members (which were previously in `Logo`).

Broke the `updateNotation` method into two parts: one remains in `Logo`, the rest of it have been moved to `doUpdateNotation` inside `Notation`.

pr_title: Port math related methods to MathUtility
pr_body:
I've moved the `math` related methods from `Logo` to `MathUtility` in a new file `utils/mathutils.js`. I've actually created the class `MathUtility`, and all methods are `static`.

I've refactored the `arg` methods corresponding to the `10` methods that I moved, in a way that `arg` methods handle only activity specific to `blocks`, while the static methods verify the input and produce results accordingly. I've used `exception handling` to communicate between the two disconnected operations.

pr_title: Fix getter/setter reference bug and refactor to add Painter class
pr_body:
- Fixed all `Turtle` related regression generated post previous port, which were caused due to referencing error for `getters` & `setters`
- Created a new component class named `Painter` which would we responsible for all visual activities of each `Turtle` - moved all activity related members to `Painter`. The `Turtle` oversees the `Painter` (I did this to make some progress on the idea that there'll be two activities: drawing and singing, and each `Turtle` object shall oversee both of these activities, independent of other `Turtle` objects; `Painter` and possibly `Singer` would be subcomponents of the `Turtle` object, rather than be part of its own MVC).

There are a lot of changes, but the idea is simple: I've moved some members from `Turtle` to `Painter`.

pr_title: Framework for text based Music Blocks code
pr_body:
Amongst all the different techniques I tried, this one seems like an nice solution to me. This is right now only a proof of concept meant for demonstration and so, it isn't polished.

The reason I like this procedure is because it uses native JavaScript features and the code is totally valid JavaScript. This procedure gives us the ability to write any JavaScript code and call our API asynchronous functions right between synchronous statements - the asynchronous functions appear to run synchronously . This syntax is somewhat clean but we can do further cleaning later on if we proceed with this.

I've added a `100ms` delay after each command so that the actions are visible individually.

pr_title: Generate block stacks tree, AST, and code
pr_body:
To generate stacks tree:
`JSGenerate.generateStacksTree()`: tree saved in `JSGenerate.startTrees` and `JSGenerate.actionTrees`

To print stacks tree:
`JSGenerate.printStacksTree()`

To generate AST and code:
`JSGenerate.generateCode()`: AST saved in `JSGenerate.AST` and code in `JSGenerate.code`

To run all in order:
`JSGenerate.run(true, true)`: first `true` is to print the stacks trees on the console; second one for the code

**Code generation though the JS Editor is now operational**

Code generated from the blocks is displayed in the editor when opened. Clicking on the generate button regenerates it.
